               <msContents>
                  <summary>Cheese Straws</summary>
                  <textLang>English</textLang>
                  <msItem>
                     <p>
                        <l>1-Cup Kraft Med or Sharp grated cheese. I use sharp</l>
                        <l>1-Stick Parkay Margarine</l>
                        <l>1-Cup flour (plain)</l>
                        <l>I add 1/8 teaspoon red pepper after after I double</l>
                        <l>this recipe!</l>
                        <l> Mix ingredients. Knead into a ball. It</l>
                        <l>should be moist. Knead like making bread</l>
                        <l>dough. Shape into very small balls. Use a</l>
                        <l>fork and mash two ways. Put on cookie sheet</l>
                        <l>after spraying with oil and cook at 350^o for</l>
                        <l>fifteen minutes. Check. You might have to cook</l>
                        <l>2 or 3 more minutes. Let cool. Place in</l>
                        <l>container. I always double recipe, sometimes triple</l>
                                                               <l> (over)</l>
                     </p>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="notecard">
                     <supportDesc material="paper">
                        <support>
                           <p>recipe card</p>
                        </support>
                        <extent> 3 x 5 <dimensions scope="all" type="leaf" unit="in">
                              <height>3</height>
                              <width>5</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <p>Nana's Handwriting</p>
                  </handDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <p>Written around <origDate>1980</origDate></p>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <desc>
                        <list>
                           <item> <persName>Nancy Frances Seats Sisk </persName>was born in 1928 in <placeName>Lewisville, NC</placeName> to a family that owned a small farm and a Mom and Pop store</item>
                           <item> This is my great grandmother <persName>Ethel Seats</persName> </item>
                           <item> Cheese straws are a <placeName>Winston-Salem, NC</placeName> favorite. They are <objectType>spicy cheese cookies </objectType>bizarre but delicious.</item>
                           <item> Nana gives my dad, <persName>Richard K. Triplette</persName> born <date>1952</date> a full Tupperware container of these every Christmas as his present.</item>
                           <item> She married my grandfather, <persName>Victor Sisk</persName>, who did not have a high school degree.</item>
                           <item> My mom, <persName>Kathy Sisk Triplette</persName>, born <date>1951</date>, is their first of two daughters.</item>
                        </list>
                     </desc>
                     <alt>
                        <!-- When I make this recipe hipster style, I substitute unsalted butter for the Parkay and
                        replace the Kraft cheese with the nicest, sharpest cheddar I can find. I reduce cooking
                        time to 10 minutes, and I quadruple the recipe to get a full tupperware container. Instead
                        of red pepper flakes I use Sriracha or my hometown hot sauce, Texas Pete, made in Winston-Salem, NC -->
                     </alt>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <desc>This is my great grandmother Ethel Seats's recipe modified by my grandmother (called Frances or Fanny) for the 1950s-1970s taste for processed food.</desc>
                     <desc>My grandmother wrote this 3 X 5 recipe card around 1980 and gave it to me at Christmas in 2014.</desc>
                  </acquisition>
